<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05174a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05174a">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05174a"> 174(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the Dagda&apos;s harp / Goltree: weep / Gartree: laugh / Soontree: sleep</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>The harp</mark> came forth from the wall then and killed nine persons in its passage. And it came to <mark>the Daghda</mark>, and he played for the three musical feats which give distinction to a harper, namely the <mark><i>Goltree</i> which from its melting plaintiveness, caused crying, the <i>Gentree</i>, which from its merriment, caused laughter, and the <i>Soontree</i>, which from its deep murmuring, causes sleep.</mark> <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="PIIP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#PIIP"><cite title="source">The Preternatural in Early Irish Poetry</cite></a>, (1912) 122</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
